    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Segment Reporting, Revenue Breakdown, Financial Performance, Comparability Disclaimers, and Integration Risk Factors\n\nBased on the provided prospectus excerpts, here is a comprehensive retrieval of the requested disclosures:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Segment Reporting — Definitions and Structure\n\nSpaceX operates **three reportable segments**:\n\n> **Space segment** — designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets to provide high cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale.\n\n> **Connectivity segment** — operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit, delivering connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers through the Starlink offering.\n\n> **AI segment** — operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning a frontier LLM (Grok), AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, X — a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform — and AI computational infrastructure.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Revenue Breakdown by Segment and Sub-Category\n\nThe prospectus provides the following revenue disaggregation categories:\n\n| Segment | Sub-Category |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Space** | Launch Services |\n| | Launch & Development |\n| **Connectivity** | Consumer |\n| | Enterprise & Government *(includes Starlink Mobile)* |\n| **AI** | Advertising |\n| | AI Solutions & Infrastructure |\n\nA footnote clarifies:\n> *"Enterprise & Government revenue includes revenue from Starlink Mobile service offerings."*\n\n### Revenue Recognition Policies by Segment\n\n- **Launch Services**: Recognized at a **point in time** upon launch/deployment, due to interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs.\n- **Launch & Development**: Recognized **over time** using the cost-to-cost input method (contracts range from one to fourteen years).\n- **Connectivity (broadband/mobile services)**: Recognized **over time** as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes benefits. Fixed-price services are recognized ratably over subscription term; variable-priced services based on actual data consumption.\n- **Starlink Kits**: Point of sale.\n- **Inter-segment Starlink launches**: No inter-segment revenue recognized; launch costs are capitalized in satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net.\n\n> *"We allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to our Connectivity segment, and expect to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future. Our Space segment revenue only reflects our customer launches and customer activities."*\n\n---\n\n## 3. Financial Performance by Segment\n\n### Space Segment\n\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|--------|---------|---------|---------|---------|---------|\n| Revenue | $4,086M | — | — | — | — |\n| Loss from operations | $(657)M | — | — | — | — |\n| Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $653M | — | — | — | — |\n| Capital expenditures (Q1 2026) | $1,052M | | | | |\n| Capital expenditures (FY 2025) | $3,832M | | | | |\n| R&D (Starship, Q1 2026) | $930M | | | | |\n| R&D (Starship, FY 2025) | $3,004M | | | | |\n\n> Revenue **decreased** $246M in Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 "due to lower Launch Services missions and timing of work for government [contracts]."\n> Cost of revenue **decreased** $16M "due to less customer launches."\n> R&D **increased** $404M "driven by accelerated investment in our Starship vehicle and related facilities."\n\n### Connectivity Segment (Starlink)\n\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|--------|---------|---------|---------|---------|---------|\n| Revenue | $3,257M | — | $11,387M | — | — |\n| Income from operations | $1,188M | $1,033M | $4,423M | $2,006M | $469M |\n| Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $2,087M | $1,618M | $7,168M | $3,849M | $1,602M |\n| Starlink Subscribers | 10.3M | 5.0M | 8.9M | 4.4M | 2.3M |\n| Starlink ARPU | $66/mo | $86/mo | $81/mo | $91/mo | $99/mo |\n| Capital expenditures (Q1 2026) | $1,332M | | | | |\n| Capital expenditures (FY 2025) | $4,178M | | | | |\n\n**FY 2025 year-over-year growth:**\n- Revenue: **+49.8%**\n- Income from operations: **+120.4%**\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA: **+86.2%**\n\n> Driven by "subscriber growth, increasing enterprise adoption, and continued improvement in network efficiency."\n\n**Q1 2026 drivers:**\n- Revenue increased $782M as "Starlink Subscriber base continued to grow."\n- Cost of revenue increased $437M "driven by an increase in depreciation related to the number of satellites placed into orbit."\n\n### AI Segment (including xAI and X/Twitter)\n\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|--------|---------|---------|---------|---------|---------|\n| Revenue | $818M | — | $3,201M | — | — |\n| Loss from operations | $(2,469)M | $(936)M | $(6,355)M | $(1,561)M | $(3,973)M |\n| Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $(609)M | $(112)M | $(1,237)M | $347M | $1,222M |\n| Nameplate compute draw (GW) | 1 | 0.3 | 0.8 | 0.3 | 0 |\n| Capital expenditures (Q1 2026) | $7,723M | | | | |\n\n**Q1 2026 drivers:**\n- Revenue increased $91M "from higher X and Grok subscriptions."\n- R&D increased $1,471M "driven by depreciation of GPU hardware, and the cost of cloud computing and data center infrastructure expenses as a result of our AI data center expansions."\n- Cost of revenue increased $5M.\n\n> *"In our newly acquired AI segment, we plan to prioritize growth and investment to capture significant opportunities in AI applications and compute infrastructure."*\n\n---\n\n## 4. Deferred Revenue\n\n> *"Deferred revenue is recorded when cash payments are received or due, in advance of the Company\'s performance. Deferred revenue primarily relates to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise and government contracts."*\n\n- Total deferred revenue as of **December 31, 2024**: **$10,179 million**\n- Of which recognized as revenue in FY 2025: **$4,080 million**\n- Total deferred revenue as of **December 31, 2025**: **$12,116 million**\n\n---\n\n## 5. Disclaimers About Comparability and Limitations of Recast Data\n\n### Retrospective Recasting for Common-Control Transactions\n\n> *"The consolidated financial statements of SpaceX have been retrospectively recast for all periods presented to include (i) the historical results of X.AI Holdings Corp., which was acquired by SpaceX, effective February 2, 2026 (the \'xAI Merger\'), and X Holdings Corp. (\'X Holdings\'), which was acquired by xAI, effective March 28, 2025 (the \'X Merger\'), because these transactions were between entities under common control, and (ii) a five-for-one stock split of the Company\'s Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock, effective May 4, 2026 (the \'2026 Stock Split\')."*\n\n> *"Unless otherwise stated or the context otherwise requires, all share and per share information included in this prospectus have been retroactively adjusted to reflect the 2026 Stock Split."*\n\n### Historical Data Limitations\n\n> *"The summary historical consolidated financial and operating data presented below is not indicative of the results to be expected for any future period, and the results for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of the results to be expected for the full fiscal period."*\n\n> *"The summary historical consolidated financial and operating data of SpaceX has been prepared to reflect the retrospective combination of the companies for all periods presented to include the historical results of xAI, which was acquired by SpaceX, effective February 2, 2026, and X Holdings, which was acquired by xAI, effective March 28, 2025, because these transactions were between entities under common control."*\n\n> *"The summary historical consolidated financial data included in this section is not intended to replace the consolidated financial statements and is qualified in its entirety by our consolidated financial statements and related notes included elsewhere in this prospectus."*\n\n> *"The following information should be read together with \'Management\'s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations\' and our consolidated financial statements and related notes thereto included elsewhere in this prospectus."*\n\n### Forward-Looking Statement Caution\n\n> *"This prospectus contains forward-looking statements that are subject to a number of risks and uncertainties, many of which are beyond our control."*\n\n---\n\n## 6. Risk Factors Related to Business Combination and Integration Risks\n\n### AI Segment Integration Risk (Primary)\n\n> *"The Company\'s AI segment is recently formed, still being integrated, operates in a rapidly evolving industry and is subject to integration, execution, competitive and operational risks."*\n\n> *"We acquired xAI in February 2026 as the foundational platform for our AI segment and as part of our ambitious vertical integration strategy intended to combine artificial intelligence capabilities with our established Space and Connectivity businesses. Prior to its acquisition by the Company, xAI itself was an early-stage company. As a result, our AI segment remains in a relatively early stage of organizational and operational maturity and is subject to integration, scaling and execution risks."*\n\n> *"The successful integration of acquired businesses, technologies, strategic partners, and employees is inherently complex, costly and time-consuming, and may result in operational inefficiencies, delays, disruptions, increased costs, loss of knowledge and diversion of management attention. As is common in large acquisitions, we have had to take significant steps to integrate xAI\'s operations into our broader corporate structure as part of our AI segment."*\n\n### Strategic Transaction Integration Risks (Broader)\n\n> *"We may not achieve the anticipated benefits, synergies, or strategic objectives of any acquisition, divestiture, or other strategic transaction in a timely manner, or at all, including those we expect from the recent acquisition of xAI, the acquisition of spectrum assets and licenses from EchoStar in connection with our Starlink Mobile initiatives, our collaboration on Terafab with Tesla, Intel or any future partners, project and our recent collaboration with Cursor and any potential acquisition of Cursor, if consummated."*\n\n> *"Acquisitions, divestitures, or other strategic transactions may present unforeseen liabilities or disruptions to our operations, which could adversely impact our business, financial condition, results of operations, and future prospects. We may assume unexpected obligations or incur costs associated with acquired businesses, including litigation, regulatory compliance, environmental liabilities, or contractual disputes, which could result in material losses or divert management focus from ongoing operations."*\n\n### Nascent Industry and Multiplanetary Risk\n\n> *"[Certain industries such as] manufacturing capabilities on the Moon and Mars, and asteroid mining, do not exist today. While we believe these industries will develop over time, the manner in which they emerge, including the timing of commercialization, the scale and pace of adoption, and the applicable competitive, technical, regulatory, geopolitical, and economic frameworks may differ materially from our current expectations."*\n\n> *"Even if such goals are achieved, they may not generate meaningful revenue or achieve profitability for an extended period of time."*\n\n---\n\n**In summary**, the prospectus discloses three segments (Space/Connectivity/AI), provides detailed revenue disaggregation with sub-categories (including Starlink Mobile within Enterprise & Government), presents segment-level profitability metrics (income from operations and Segment Adjusted EBITDA) with historical trends, and includes multiple layers of comparability disclaimers—most critically that all historical periods have been retrospectively recast to include xAI (acquired Feb 2026) and X Holdings (acquired Mar 2025) as common-control transactions, making cross-period comparisons potentially misleading given the AI segment\'s early-stage, pre-integration nature.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=35.469,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
